asons begins, be careful, be safe\nADVERTISEMENT\nEDUCATION\nPatriot Perspective: Eagle View Elementary School focuses on multi-tiered systems of support\nThe school wants parents to be involved in this process\nMaking the Grade: Nov. 30, 2022\nEagle View Elementary School student wins environmental stewardship award\nPequot Lakes students attend Young Author's Conference in Staples\nBUSINESS\nScheibes are giants in the small world of ag toys\nSeventh creative Christmas tree ball gown unveiled at Crosslake store\nLakewood Health System's new robot delivers\nTHE VAULT\nThis Minnesota man went missing without a trace. 7 years later, there are still no answers\nBefore there were American Legions or VFWs, Civil War veterans built this place in Minnesota\nThis tiny Minnesota town's wild legacy: 2 bank robberies, a train derailment, unsolved wildfires\nLIFESTYLE\nItalian Butter Sweets are festive, easy-to-make and delicious\nFood columnist Sarah Nasello will give away a dozen Italian Butter Sweets next week as part of her weekly SarahBakes Holiday Giveaway.\nMEMBERS ONLY\nChef's Hat: The mystery of white chocolate\nSenior Meals: Pine River nutrition site menus listed for Dec. 5-9, 2022\nMEMBERS ONLY\nThe Cracker Barrel: Grandpa's gift\nOPINION\nLetter to the Editor: Green burial sought, denied\nGrim's Tales: An early look back and an earlier look ahead\nBy  Travis G. Grimler\nLetter to the Editor: Commissioner-elect shares his gratitude\nBy  Jon Lubke\nMN StarWatch: Our moon occults Mars Dec. 7\nBy  Deane Morrison\nADVERTISEMENT\nHEALTH\nTest your holiday health smarts with this seasonal quiz\nWest Fargo girl's bout with RSV offers cautionary tale for parents\nWant to unlock the secret to waking up refreshed and alert? Do these three things\nMINNESOTA\nPolice: St. Paul officer fatally shoots man armed with gun\nDuluth looks to 'tiny homes' to help ease housing crunch\nSeveral Minnesota hospital systems reach tentative agreements with nurses\nKLICK ECHO JOURNAL\nklick! Pho